
Problem Analysis (Global + India)
Project Context: FacePass Travel
FacePass Travel replaces tickets, cards, and physical IDs with a face-based digital travel identity, enabling seamless, contactless, and secure travel across airports, railways, metros, buses, hotels, and checkpoints.
________________________________________
1. Global Problem Analysis
1.1 Fragmented Travel Identity Systems
●	Travelers globally are required to carry multiple physical items: tickets, boarding passes, passports/IDs, access cards, visas, hotel keys, and loyalty cards.
●	Each system operates in silos (airlines, airports, immigration, rail, hotels), causing repeated verification and inefficiency.
●	Lack of a single, universal digital identity leads to friction at every travel touchpoint.
1.2 Time-Consuming Verification & Queues
●	Manual ID checks and document scanning create long queues at:
○	Airport check-in & boarding gates
○	Immigration & security
○	Railway stations and metro entry points
●	Peak travel seasons amplify delays, missed connections, and traveler dissatisfaction.
1.3 Security & Fraud Risks
●	Physical tickets and IDs are vulnerable to:
○	Loss and theft
○	Duplication and forgery
○	Impersonation and ticket transfer fraud
●	Identity mismatch remains a major security concern in global transportation systems.
1.4 Poor Contactless Readiness
●	The post-pandemic world has accelerated demand for touch-free travel, yet many systems still depend on:
○	Physical document handling
○	Fingerprint or card-based access
●	Inconsistent biometric adoption limits scalability and user trust.
1.5 High Operational Costs
●	Airlines, airports, and transit authorities spend heavily on:
○	Staffing for identity checks
○	Hardware for ticketing and access control
○	Fraud management and dispute resolution
●	Inefficient verification increases operational expenditure and carbon footprint.
