2. India-Specific Problem Analysis
2.1 Massive Passenger Volume
●	India is among the world’s largest travel markets with:
○	High daily footfall in railways, metros, and buses
○	Rapid growth in domestic air travel
●	Existing systems struggle to handle scale and speed simultaneously.
2.2 Dependency on Physical Proofs
●	Travelers often carry:
○	Printed tickets or PDFs
○	Aadhaar, PAN, Voter ID, or passports
●	Loss of documents leads to denied entry, delays, or manual intervention.
2.3 Infrastructure Bottlenecks
●	Crowded stations and airports face:
○	Manual ticket checks
○	Limited entry/exit gates
○	Human-dependent verification
●	This results in congestion, safety risks, and poor passenger experience.
2.4 Fraud & Ticket Misuse
●	Common issues include:
○	Ticket resale and sharing
○	Fake or altered IDs
○	Unauthorized entry using borrowed documents
●	Enforcement is inconsistent due to reliance on human checks.
2.5 Digital Divide & Usability Challenges
●	While India has strong digital infrastructure, travel systems still rely on:
○	Apps, QR codes, OTPs, or SMS
●	These fail when phones are lost, batteries die, or networks are weak.
●	A face-based identity removes device dependency.
